WEBVTT

1
00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:27.382
I was born in Yuma, Arizona
in a ranch owned by my family


2
00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:29.861
but we lost it in the depression.

3
00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:35.110
Like many other families, we moved
to California to work in the fields.


4
00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:38.702
<i>But when we arrived, we found out that
there was more people than jobs.</i>


5
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:42.984
<i>We went from being farm owners
to farm workers in one day.</i>


6
00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:47.502
<i>And at the age of 11,
I started working in the fields.</i>


7
00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:50.348
<i>That's where I witnessed,
for the first time,</i>


8
00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:54.266
<i>the injustice and the indignities
suffered by the farm workers.</i>


9
00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:58.707
<i>You see the problem is that in 1936
the country changed,</i>


10
00:02:59.420 --> 00:03:02.071
<i>because the National Labor Relations Act
went into effect.</i>


11
00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:06.988
And it gave most workers the right
to join the union and bargain collectively.


12
00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:09.469
Except the farm workers,

13
00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:14.023
they were excluded from this protection
and I was one of them.


14
00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:18.862
I wanted to do something, so I joined
the CSO, Community Services Organization.


15
00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:21.462
And that is where I learned
how to organize people.


16
00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:26.348
<i>We were working in the cities and I
realized that, to make a difference,</i>


17
00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:29.503
<i>I had to get out
and start organizing the workers.</i>


18
00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:33.665
<i>So, in 1962, I went back
to the fields to do just that.</i>


19
00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:38.423
Juan de la Cruz!

20
00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:43.665
I'm a friend of your cousin, Felipe.

21
00:04:50.580 --> 00:04:51.706
Are you Juan?

22
00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:53.381
Can we talk?

23
00:04:53.740 --> 00:04:56.186
Sure. But not here.

24
00:05:01.260 --> 00:05:03.740
I'm done in about four hours.

25
00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:15.390
You need to leave now. 
They're coming.

26
00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:27.550
Can I help you, sir?
Were you talking to those workers?


27
00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:30.426
Is there something I can do for you?

28
00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:33.184
I'm talking to you.

29
00:05:40.140 --> 00:05:42.381
Do you own anything?

30
00:05:47.220 --> 00:05:48.221
No.

31
00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:53.347
Can you read or write?

32
00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:58.465
Well... No.

33
00:05:59.180 --> 00:06:00.591
Of course not.

34
00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:10.347
Who in your family works?

35
00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:17.380
Me and my wife.

36
00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:22.505
And my kids. The older ones anyways.

37
00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:26.380
The other ones are still too young.

38
00:06:29.020 --> 00:06:31.421
Do you want more for your kids?

39
00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:34.944
Of course.

40
00:06:37.540 --> 00:06:38.871
But...

41
00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:46.341
Most of the people are afraid.

42
00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:51.583
They have to feed their kids.

43
00:06:58.740 --> 00:07:01.584
It's not easy doing it alone.

44
00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:09.068
I'll return in one month
to help you start organizing.


45
00:07:09.580 --> 00:07:12.629
But I need you to gather
everyone you can here.


46
00:07:17.540 --> 00:07:19.030
OK, that's fine.

47
00:07:20.060 --> 00:07:22.711
And you won't be alone anymore.

48
00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:27.223
If we want to organize farm workers,
if we're really serious,


49
00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:28.980
it's not gonna happen here, not with them.

50
00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:33.749
It's just one setback, Cesar, it takes a while
to build trust, you have to be patient.


51
00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:35.788
You know, they really don't care about
the farm worker, Fred.


52
00:07:35.900 --> 00:07:36.901
Gilbert, that's not true.

53
00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:40.348
See that's what I'm talking about, Fred,
see I have to be where it's happening.


54
00:07:40.420 --> 00:07:43.151
I have to get out of Los Angeles
and go back to the fields where I started.


55
00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:45.143
You know, we are doing this together, okay?

56
00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:47.382
You knew this could happen,
that is why we have a plan.


57
00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:49.346
But not in an office.

58
00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:50.706
It's not the time to walk out now.

59
00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:52.384
You know what it takes,
that is why I brought you in.


60
00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:55.947
The CSO will be behind you, no matter what,
but please at least sleep on it.


61
00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:57.266
I am not tired, Fred.

62
00:07:58.340 --> 00:07:59.830
I want to get my hands dirty.

63
00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:03.231
- Cesar...
- I'm with him. He's right.


64
00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:07.906
You will go to new schools
and make new friends.


65
00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:11.468
You're going to be fine.

66
00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:14.150
Your father and I
grew up on the fields.

67
00:08:14.220 --> 00:08:15.710
Which team plays for Delano?

68
00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:21.628
Your tio Ruc and tia Petra live in Delano,
so do our cousins. It's gonna be good.


69
00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:23.829
Okay, let's take a vote.

70
00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:26.422
Who wants to go to Delano?

71
00:08:37.660 --> 00:08:39.822
<i>...a wonderful day
in Southern California.</i>


72
00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:41.829
<i>- Sandy Koufax on the mound.
- No!</i>


73
00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:44.910
<i>Sandy coming off that
beautiful no-hitter last week.</i>


74
00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:48.065
<i>Caullison just waving that bat
back and forth.</i>


75
00:08:48.180 --> 00:08:50.148
<i>- Pare,</i> I <i>am trying</i> to listen to <i>the game.
- Koufax trying to keep</i>


76
00:08:50.220 --> 00:08:51.381
<i>his winning streak going.</i>

77
00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:54.191
Could you stop? Stop!

78
00:08:58.580 --> 00:09:01.345
<i>Top of the fourth,
Dodgers leading two to nothing.</i>


79
00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:06.188
<i>Koufax delivers and it's
a line drive down the left field line...</i>


80
00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:07.347
<i>Fair ball!</i>

81
00:09:13.540 --> 00:09:15.861
I can't hear. Can you turn it up?

82
00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:18.986
I think we, uh, lost the signal.

83
00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:22.466
You promised me a three-bedroom house.

84
00:09:22.540 --> 00:09:24.144
I said I would try, Mansi.
It was short notice.


85
00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:25.300
But I gave you two months.

86
00:09:25.660 --> 00:09:26.786
That's short notice!

87
00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:28.100
Uncle Cesar.

88
00:09:28.300 --> 00:09:30.780
- That goes in the bedroom, Chato.
- It doesn't fit.


89
00:09:30.860 --> 00:09:31.907
It doesn't fit.

90
00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:33.869
Hey, Cesar, we've lived in a lot worse.

91
00:09:33.940 --> 00:09:34.941
We'll be fine.

92
00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:36.346
Can you get the heavy stuff
in the truck please?


93
00:09:37.540 --> 00:09:40.510
If you put eight kids in that one car,
you can put them in that house!


94
00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:42.943
We can find a bigger one
in a couple of months.


95
00:09:43.060 --> 00:09:45.142
And then we gotta
move all over again?


96
00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:14.383
Forty-eight, forty-nine,

97
00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:16.750
fifty, fifty-one,

98
00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:18.945
fifty-two,

99
00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:20.985
fifty-three!

100
00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:23.461
That's all for today!

101
00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:26.181
I hear they are looking for bodies
at the onion fields.


102
00:10:54.300 --> 00:10:56.268
I found the same thing in Hanford.

103
00:10:56.900 --> 00:10:58.629
The workers are scared.

104
00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:03.709
Then we need to hold twice as many
house meetings than we did in Selma.


105
00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:15.707
- What's the matter?
- It's my back.


106
00:11:19.820 --> 00:11:21.470
You can't take real work anymore.

107
00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:23.622
It hurts even when I don't work.

108
00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:25.623
You should take it easy.

109
00:11:26.100 --> 00:11:29.024
What, and live on just
what Helen makes? No.


110
00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:32.549
We are going to make the kids work
on the weekends now.


111
00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:39.344
but she went and told everybody
at the church,


112
00:11:39.460 --> 00:11:40.825
and now everybody has...

113
00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:42.387
Look who is here.

114
00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:44.624
And very dirty.

115
00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:47.105
Did you walk here from Oxnard?

116
00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:48.227
Ola.

117
00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:49.901
I thought maybe you weren't coming back.

118
00:11:50.300 --> 00:11:52.302
- It's only been two weeks.
- It's been 18 days.


119
00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:53.381
Eighteen days...

120
00:11:54.180 --> 00:11:55.181
Cesar.

121
00:11:56.340 --> 00:11:57.387
Dolores!

122
00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:02.468
Look at you.
You definitely got your hands dirty.


123
00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:05.381
This is Angela. Say, "Hi, Cesar."

124
00:12:05.460 --> 00:12:06.791
Hey, mamita.

125
00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:08.101
I'm gonna put her to bed.

126
00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:09.989
How long are you guys visiting us?

127
00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:12.984
Oh, well, word is you can't
do this without me, so...


128
00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:15.341
You are staying?

129
00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:19.306
Well, of course. You think I'm going to
let you mess up what you've started here?


130
00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:23.066
But before you do anything,
you need to go talk to Fernando.


131
00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:28.264
I need to go talk to Fernando?

132
00:12:29.660 --> 00:12:30.707
Okay.

133
00:12:52.940 --> 00:12:54.066
Hi, Poli.

134
00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:00.144
What happened to your eye?

135
00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:01.746
Nothing.

136
00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:07.547
You wanna talk about this nothing?

137
00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:08.746
Nope.

138
00:13:13.580 --> 00:13:15.628
The kids here are idiots.

139
00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:19.269
They hate us, you know?

140
00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:23.865
<i>They came up on me and Chats,
a bunch of them.</i>


141
00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:27.740
They wouldn't stop calling us "beaners."

142
00:13:27.860 --> 00:13:31.069
Beaners? Is that the best they got?

143
00:13:33.620 --> 00:13:35.748
I've been called much worse.

144
00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:40.270
<i>â€œGreaser,</i>

145
00:13:41.860 --> 00:13:42.861
"wetback,

146
00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:45.906
"spic."

147
00:13:46.180 --> 00:13:48.547
That one doesn't even make sense.

148
00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:50.221
"Brown nigger."

149
00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:52.829
I never heard that one.

150
00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:53.981
Uh-huh.

151
00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:55.744
I learned a lot in the Navy.

152
00:13:58.300 --> 00:14:00.143
Here, put this on your eye.

153
00:14:04.020 --> 00:14:05.590
Who started it?

154
00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:08.269
I told you, they started calling us names.

155
00:14:08.620 --> 00:14:09.985
No, who started the fight?

156
00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:13.507
We didn't have a choice.

157
00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:16.422
You always have a choice.

158
00:14:20.900 --> 00:14:22.982
I knew you wouldn't get it.

159
00:14:39.860 --> 00:14:41.942
<i>although the
official military word is that</i>


160
00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:44.068
<i>these are only mopping up operations,</i>

161
00:14:44.180 --> 00:14:45.944
<i>in five separate actions...</i>

162
00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:48.307
We need to bring the
people together, like a convention.


163
00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:50.382
We need to get
everybody together in one place


164
00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:52.184
so they can see how strong we are.

165
00:14:52.260 --> 00:14:54.228
We should start a credit union.

166
00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:55.865
To loan people money?

167
00:14:55.940 --> 00:14:58.621
It'll give us credibility
and it will help people during the winter.


168
00:14:59.340 --> 00:15:01.866
<i>Hey, remember me? 
Eli Ordonez.</i>

169
00:15:02.340 --> 00:15:04.547
I saw you in Salinas at that other meeting
you were doing.


170
00:15:04.620 --> 00:15:06.702
If you want, I
can help pass those around.

171
00:15:07.100 --> 00:15:09.546
I have a cousin who has no papers.

172
00:15:09.660 --> 00:15:11.389
You tell your cousin,
if he works in the fields,


173
00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:13.508
he has the right to representation.

174
00:15:15.860 --> 00:15:17.703
What is happening here in Delano

175
00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:20.546
is the same thing that is happening
in Salinas or in Stockton.


176
00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:24.184
If we don't get organized,
the bosses are going to treat us like...


177
00:15:24.260 --> 00:15:25.591
Excuse me.

178
00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:27.426
Who are you?

179
00:15:28.660 --> 00:15:29.741
Cesar Chavez.

180
00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:38.940
How much are you
asking for, Chucho?


181
00:15:39.300 --> 00:15:40.586
Twenty-five dollars.

182
00:15:41.380 --> 00:15:42.506
How about 10, Chucho?

183
00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:44.821
Look at all these other people
who also want money.


184
00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:47.900
My daughter has some questionnaires.

185
00:15:48.100 --> 00:15:50.182
We want to know what concerns you.

186
00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:51.711
Come on, just do that for us.

187
00:16:01.900 --> 00:16:06.701
Here, people can put messages
to their family, or anyone, it's free.


188
00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:10.823
Want to see the union paper?

189
00:16:42.060 --> 00:16:43.425
Sheriff, every night this goes on.

190
00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:45.180
And I have to tell
my husband to rush home

191
00:16:45.220 --> 00:16:47.188
because I'm frightened
about what is going on over there.


192
00:16:47.260 --> 00:16:48.910
We are decent folk
and don't want any trouble.


193
00:16:48.980 --> 00:16:51.631
I'm terrified for my children
and who knows where...


194
00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:54.704
Okay... Okay... Ladies... Ladies...
Let me make sure I understand this.


195
00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:57.101
- You say they get together every night?
- Every night.


196
00:16:57.180 --> 00:16:58.181
And there is 50 of them?

197
00:16:58.260 --> 00:17:00.740
Fifty-seven. I count 57.

198
00:17:01.620 --> 00:17:02.746
Fifty-seven?

199
00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:13.341
Mr. Chavez?

200
00:17:15.020 --> 00:17:16.146
Yes?

201
00:17:16.220 --> 00:17:17.460
How are you doin' today?

202
00:17:17.540 --> 00:17:19.861
Fine. How can I help you?

203
00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:21.710
I just wanted to introduce myself.

204
00:17:21.820 --> 00:17:23.300
- I'm Sheriff...
- I know who you are.


205
00:17:26.380 --> 00:17:29.031
You seem to be gathering quite a crowd.

206
00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:30.941
Is there a law against that?

207
00:17:31.460 --> 00:17:33.861
No, not really.

208
00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:37.744
But I would like
to ask you some questions

209
00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:41.667
about some of the people around you
and their affiliations.


210
00:17:41.940 --> 00:17:43.101
Affiliations to what?

211
00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:45.709
Let's say the communist party.

212
00:17:46.220 --> 00:17:47.824
- Communists?
- Yes.


213
00:17:53.540 --> 00:17:55.269
Do you mind tellin' me what's so funny?

214
00:17:56.580 --> 00:17:58.389
It's that we are Catholic.

215
00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:00.391
How can Catholics be communists?

216
00:18:02.420 --> 00:18:04.229
I've seen stranger things.

217
00:18:04.460 --> 00:18:07.191
Mr. Chavez, do you mind
if we take a look around?


218
00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:09.661
Do you have a warrant?

219
00:18:14.260 --> 00:18:15.341
Not on me.

220
00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:17.745
So you're asking me for a favor?

221
00:18:18.340 --> 00:18:19.941
I think you'd be doing yourself a favor.

222
00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:23.751
Come on. There's nothing to see here.

223
00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:26.106
Come in.

224
00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:28.870
We have nothing to hide.

225
00:18:29.020 --> 00:18:31.421
So what they doin' here?

226
00:18:32.220 --> 00:18:33.900
You givin' away free pinatas or something?

227
00:18:34.820 --> 00:18:36.026
It's a credit union.

228
00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:38.981
No shit.

229
00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:40.466
Where's the money coming from?

230
00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:41.826
Donations.

231
00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:47.465
Here's a box if you're interested.

232
00:18:58.860 --> 00:19:01.704
I don't know exactly
what you're up to here

233
00:19:02.220 --> 00:19:04.222
but the citizens of Delano,

234
00:19:04.580 --> 00:19:06.867
they don't care much for subversives.

235
00:19:08.060 --> 00:19:09.869
They respect the law.

236
00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:12.826
So do we.

237
00:19:14.180 --> 00:19:16.421
Especially the Bill of Rights.

238
00:19:17.940 --> 00:19:19.829
Ever read the Bill of Rights?

239
00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:31.300
Let's go.

240
00:19:41.900 --> 00:19:43.940
<i>Listen up, all of you in there.</i>

241
00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:46.221
<i>You have 10 minutes
to vacate the premises.</i>


242
00:19:46.820 --> 00:19:51.382
<i>You are now trespassing and will be
prosecuted to the full extent of the law.</i>


243
00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:52.700
We are not moving!

244
00:19:54.220 --> 00:19:55.267
<i>Is that you, Larry?</i>

245
00:19:56.180 --> 00:19:58.148
Yeah. Yeah, it's me.

246
00:19:58.420 --> 00:20:01.469
<i>Larry, you get your people out of there now
and get back to work.</i>


247
00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:05.461
<i>I'll forget everything.
No blacklisting, no nothing.</i>


248
00:20:07.660 --> 00:20:10.140
Sorry, that's not good enough.

